# Cerebro — Core Rules

## What This Project Is
Cerebro is an autonomous AI agent system built for FutureVault. It contains two agents — a Compliance Agent and an Onboarding Agent — that monitor client document vaults and take autonomous action. Always refer to @docs/blueprint.md for the full project description before making architectural decisions.

## Stack — Never Deviate From This
- **Framework:** Next.js 15 App Router
- **Language:** TypeScript — strict mode always on, no `any` types ever
- **Agent Framework:** Mastra (`@mastra/core`, `@mastra/memory`, `@mastra/evals`)
- **AI Model Gateway:** OpenRouter via `@openrouter/ai-sdk-provider`
- **Database:** PostgreSQL via Prisma ORM on Supabase
- **Queue:** BullMQ with Upstash Redis
- **UI:** Tailwind CSS v4 + shadcn/ui components
- **Charts:** Recharts
- **Email:** Resend
- **Validation:** Zod — everywhere, always
- **Testing:** Vitest

## Absolute Rules — Never Break These

### Models
- Never hardcode a model string like `"google/gemini-2.0-flash"` outside of `src/lib/config.ts`
- Always use `getModel("dev" | "demo" | "evalJudge")` from `@/lib/config`
- Default to `"dev"` tier during all development — it is the cheapest

### Database Access
- Raw Prisma queries are NEVER written inside `src/tools/` or `src/agents/`
- ALL database access from tools goes through `VaultService` only
- `VaultService` is always constructed with a `clientId` — it is never constructed without one
- Never import `prisma` directly in any file under `src/tools/` or `src/agents/`

### Validation
- Every function that accepts external input must validate with Zod before doing anything
- Every Mastra tool must have both `inputSchema` and `outputSchema` defined as Zod schemas
- Never use `z.any()` — define the actual shape

### Configuration
- Never read `process.env` directly anywhere except `src/lib/config.ts`
- Always import the validated `env` object from `@/lib/config`
- All date logic uses `env.DEMO_DATE` — never `new Date()` directly

### Agents
- The single `Mastra` instance lives at `src/agents/mastra.ts` — nowhere else
- Agents are never instantiated or run from Next.js route handlers
- Route handlers enqueue BullMQ jobs — the BullMQ worker runs agents
- Agent memory is always configured — never create an agent without memory

### TypeScript
- Enable `strict: true` in tsconfig — no exceptions
- Prefer `type` imports over `import` for type-only usage
- Name all Zod schemas with suffix `Schema` e.g. `clientProfileSchema`
- Name all TypeScript types derived from Zod with `z.infer` e.g. `type ClientProfile = z.infer<typeof clientProfileSchema>`

### File Naming
- Agent files: `src/agents/[agentName]/agent.ts`
- Tool files: `src/tools/[category]/[toolName].ts` — one tool per file
- Use camelCase for all filenames except Next.js route segments

### Error Handling
- Never swallow errors silently — always log to the audit trail
- Throw descriptive error messages that explain what failed and why
- BullMQ handles retries — tools should throw on failure, not return error objects

### Comments
- Write comments that explain WHY, not WHAT
- Every exported function must have a JSDoc comment
- Mark every compliance-related rule with `// REGULATORY:` so it is easily searchable

## Project Structure Reference
Always follow the directory structure defined in @docs/architecture.md. Never create files outside the defined structure without a good reason and updating the architecture doc.

## Dry Run Mode
- Check `env.DRY_RUN` before sending any email, webhook, or external call
- Database writes always happen regardless of dry run mode
- Tests and evals always run in dry run mode — never send real emails during testing
